🍻BEER + MIMOLETTE🧀⠀
⠀
Sabrina (@sabsmeow) and I had the pleasure of creating some fun and unique beer pairings with this incredible cheese - Mimolette from @isignyamerica. We had a variety from 3-24 month cave aged. Overall the cheese was salty, tangy, mildly fruity and smoky, buttery, and nutty. As we made our way through towards the longest aged cheese, the flavor intensified, and the texture because more firm. ⠀
Watch the video and read below to see which beers we chose for the different ages. 👇🏼⠀
⠀
🧀3 Month Mimolette + Hoppy Pilsner from @saintarcherbrew⠀
When pairing food and beer, it’s best to match flavor intensities. We thought something light and easy drinking would be perfect for the youngest cheese. This cheese was the most spongey and pliable of the bunch. It definitely gave off more of a creamy, buttery texture. The effervescence from the beer was perfect for cutting through the creaminess and cleansing the palate. I would use this cheese on a burger or in a grilled cheese, as it is the easiest to melt.⠀
⠀
⠀
🧀6 Month + The Harlot from @SocieteBrewing⠀
Still fairly mild in terms of flavor. The saltiness was on the more subtle side. A bit firmer in texture. We felt like the flavor intensities were comparable- the softness of the pilsner malt doesn’t overpower the cheese. I felt the saltiness of the cheese made the fruity esters in the beer seem a bit more prominent as well as refreshing/thirst quenching. ⠀
⠀
⠀
🧀12 Month + Fest Bier, one from @Societebrewing and one from @SaintArcherbrew⠀
This is where we started to notice more of a difference in flavors and texture. The salt and firmness were kicked up quite a bit. This cheese had some really pleasant crystallization, which we hadn’t noticed in the younger cheeses. The Fest Biers both had a caramel like sweetness to them which was pretty tasty with the salt and crystallization. A delicious and seasonally appropriate pairing.⠀
⠀

node.text:
Beyond stoked that this past weekend I got to see @msgladysknight live with a local beer in hand at a stunning new music venue. 😍 🎶 🍻 I have a few of her albums on vinyl and it was a real treat watching her perform.⁣
⁣
The @sandiegosymphony just opened @theshellsd downtown in South Embarcadero Park San Diego. The venue is in a gorgeous location—we got to watch the sun set over the water while @naturally7 opened for Gladys Knight. ⁣
⁣
The Shell is packed with a ton of great food and 🍻LOCAL BEER🍻. ⁣
⁣
They have a lot of great performances lined up, and I can’t wait to visit again. 🎼

#TBT ⚡️
My phone shot me a little tbt this morning. This photo is from 4 years ago, right before I left Refuge. It got me thinking about all of the different brew decks I’ve spent time on. I’m grateful to have such a range of experience with brewhouses—old, new, big, small, and from various manufacturers. Brewing and learning on all different types of equipment was challenging—but to me that’s another fun part of brewing. Never stop learning and growing 🙌

node.text:
Yesterday Societe hosted ⁣
✨🌈QUEER FOLK UNITE🌈✨⁣
⁣
This was my first time coordinating a real event. I don’t work in events and I never have. But my LGBTQ+ family, friends, community, is something I am extremely passionate about and what really drove this project for me. ⁣
⁣
QFU was (and is) many things to me. It was providing the community a safe and welcoming space to express themselves authentically through their creative outlets. A way to give back to local organizations doing incredible work. A place to celebrate even after Pride is technically “over” (according to the calendar). ⁣
⁣
And that’s just it—Pride is never over. Not for me. Not for my community. As a “feminine” presenting lesbian I have to come out every single day. We deal with discrimination and hatred, constantly assessing places and people to ensure our safety. Being able to live and love authentically is something I’ll never take for granted—and also something I’ll never stop fighting for. ⁣
⁣
This wasn’t a one time event, effort, celebration. ⁣
⁣
Next time you want to brew a rainbow beer, or make a rainbow t-shirt, throw a Pride event, etc. Make sure your support doesn’t stop there. Because Pride and true allyship is YEAR ROUND. ⁣
⁣
Cheers, y’all 🍺🌈✨⁣
⁣
⁣
A HUGE thank you to my work for saying “hell yeah, how can we help?” when I asked to throw a Pride event. To my coworkers who co-organized this event, worked the bar, and lent a hand however they could, donated their tips, showed up and supported the creators. ⁣
⁣
Thank you to the creators who made it out and brought their amazing art:⁣
⁣
🌈 @prismpride_co ⁣
🌈 @camdowncam ⁣
🌈 @heygayshop ⁣
🌈 @solacefloral ⁣
🌈 @wickywomancandles ⁣
🌈 @purple_panther_vintage ⁣
⁣
Funds from this event went towards @thehouseofresilience. A local organization providing 100% free aid to trans woc. 💕 You can also donate directly through their page.⁣
⁣
There are still a few shirts available at Societe. If we have excess, they’ll be in our online store. ⁣
⁣
❤️🧡💛💚💙💜🖤🤎

node.text:
I haven’t really taken any trips in a longgg time (we all haven’t), but visiting Portland has been extra special. The weather has been fantastic, the scenery is beautiful, and my little beer heart is warm and fuzzy from spending time with my bad ass brewer friends. I can’t really describe the bond between women and queers in the industry when we get together, but it’s been ✨magical✨. Thanks for welcoming me into your little crew for the weekend. ⁣
⁣
And a big thanks to Zak, Joey, and the team at @crosbyhops and @topwirehp. Drinking great local beer while surrounded by fields of hops (and so many dogs) is also pretty dang magical. 🌱🍻⁣
⁣
Beers:⁣
🍺CZ AF - @wayfinderbeer ⁣
🍺Deseo (Latin Lager) @sunriverbrewing

node.text:
📣 JOURNALISTS. WRITERS. PODCASTERS...⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I’m challenging you to stop writing and speaking *solely* about the problems of racism, homophobia, sexism, ableism, etc—that exist within the beer industry... and start also including the steps people can take to start making changes. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Shine a light on breweries, individuals, and groups that are making ✨genuine✨ efforts towards a more inclusive + equitable industry and how they are doing so. End your articles or podcasts with actionable items and resources. Use your platforms, your voices, and help people learn how they can go from good intentioned supporters to allies. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We all know there’s a problem. Let’s DO something about it. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
**from this point on I will no longer accept any interviews that only rehash trauma and don’t contribute to moving the industry forward in some way. ⁣
⁣
❗️Your actionable item today from me: (safety permitting) add your pronouns to your social media, and your work email sign offs. *This is just a very small first step. Don’t stop there.

node.text:
This was the most miserable I’ve ever been in my brewing career. Can you tell? ⁣
⁣
I’ve always been extremely passionate about equality, but I didn’t start actively and consistently fighting for it in a very public and vocal way until a few years ago. I felt like I had no other option. I spent lunch breaks crying in my car from the severity of harassment and bullying I endured. I felt so alone, and without much support. I ended up in a place so low, I don’t feel comfortable sharing it with you all. ⁣⁣
I transitioned from sharing my brewing adventures on this platform, to fighting for change. I didn’t want women(/people) who entered this industry after me to have similar experiences.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I have a lot of emotions and mixed feelings about everything coming to the surface, and the light that’s being shined on these issues. I am so grateful things are *starting* to happen to encourage change and growth. I feel more confident and empowered to actually name the companies and people who hurt me. But I am also heartbroken. I’m heartbroken for all the women and people who have had to experience these awful things. I’m heartbroken that an industry I love so much has let me down so many times. I’m heartbroken that my own stories weren’t enough for people to stop supporting my abusers. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I’m exhausted (we all are). I’m tired of excuses and the entire industry brushing shit off. I’m tired of being treated like I’m a “crazy, dramatic woman” for speaking up. I am tired of apologetic messages from people not standing up when they should have (it hurts right now). I’m tired of men apologizing in general (I don’t want your apologies I want action). I’m tired of breweries, guilds, the brewers association, etc not taking REAL action for REAL change. I’m tired of people pretending to be interested in change, but not putting in the work. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
It’s not my job as a gay woman to tell you how to be a true ally. Or to continue to relive my trauma to push you to want to do something. The information is out there. Put in the work. If you care—then fucking do something about it. ⁣

Next time when I tell my stories. They’ll include names.
